<h1>@HI{{sugiru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> V@masustem{{}} <strong>@HI{{sugiru}}</strong>
<li> @Aistem{{}} <strong>@HI{{sugiru}}</strong>
<li> @Anastem{{}} <strong>@HI{{sugiru}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<strong>@HI{{sugiru}}</strong> is an auxiliary that adds the meaning of "too much" or "to excess".
</br>
It is usually used to indicate an undesirable state.
</br>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono @KT{{apa-to}}ha @KJ{{private^accomplished}} ni ha @KJ{{tall}}<strong>sugimasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This apartment is too expensive for us.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{yuube o@KJ{{sake}}wo @KJ{{drink}}mi<strong>sugimashita</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I drank too much last night.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

@HI{{ii}} combines with @HI{{<strong>sugiru}}</strong> to form @HI{{<strong>yosugiru</strong>}}.
</br>

The negative @HI{{nai}} combines with @HI{{<strong>sugiru</strong>}} to form @HI{{<strong>nanasugiru</strong>}}.
</br>

The "for" in "too ~ for something" is formed by @HI{{ni ha}}.
</br>

<strong>@HI{{sugiru}}</strong> is an @1D{{}} verb.
</br>

